metadata.name: filter (physical postcards) #14
metadata.description:
Each minted iteration includes a 1/1 plotter-drawn physical postcard (10x15 cm / 4x6 inches) sent anywhere in the world as letter post.

The colors of the iteration determine the colors for the ink and paper that will be used for the postcard. I use heavy-weight archival paper and all inks are archival as well. 

Since this project was developed to be plotted, it may not look its best at smaller screen sizes or on mobile devices. Use the live view mode on a bigger screen for the best viewing experience. The plotted postcard will probably look slightly different than what you see on screen, because the line-width probably won't be exactly the same, and the colors might also look a bit different. 
 
To get your postcard, simply send me your address and your iteration number as a DM on twitter. I respect your privacy, and won't share your name/address with anyone.

Please note that you can't claim a postcard if you already listed your iteration for sale.

After you send me your address, it might take me a couple of weeks to plot and send your postcard (depending, of course, on how many people claim their postcards at once). Please be patient. I'll let you know when I send it. Follow me on twitter for any updates/news on the project.
 
All postcards will be sent through postal service as regular letter post with no tracking. They will be posted in a regular stamped envelope with some cardboard padding added for protection. This is both to keep the price affordable and to prevent any issues with customs. It is also the authentic postcard experience. But it also means that, depending on where you live, it might take a couple of months before your postcard arrives. Please be patient. I'm located in Germany, so collectors in Europe will probably get their cards faster. If you're willing to pay an additional fee, I can also send your card as a parcel with a tracking number and in better packaging.

---

If you're purchasing this on the secondary market:

Before purchasing, please check the link:
filterfx.carrd.co 
for information on which postcards have been already claimed, and try to get one which still has the postcard available, because if the previous owner hasn't claimed a postcard, you can still get a free postcard. 

If you purchased an iteration where the previous owner has already claimed the postcard: sorry, you can't have a postcard of that iteration, because there can be one of each postcard. But you can contact me and I'll make sure you get a physical postcard from my next postcard-related project.

---

All postcards should be claimed until 31 December 2022.



thresfold, March 2022
made with p5.js

metadata.name: Trame communale #6
metadata.description:
What does it mean to live together? What is the plan? What are we doing here? By that, I do not mean that I want to know what you are doing as an individual person, but rather what the whole of us is to achieve. Am I responsible for myself or am I responsible for you too? Am I responsible for what every single person does, or for what we collectively do as a group? Both? Neither? 

What does it mean to live together?

===

Trame communale is a generative architecture project.

The generator is made to produce 64 iterations of buildings whose structures are consistent with most plastic bricks brands.

Iterations can be virtually loaded in the anaverse under a new "village" system, which loads them all in a same space (positioned according to their order of creation).

Every owner inhabits the same commune.

metadata.name: Rapport #109
metadata.description:
The concept of nexus is a powerful one. It speaks to the idea that everything is related and that each part is necessary to create the whole. Rapport is about the relationship these parts have, harmonious or discordant, to convey a sense of unity and purpose. You are invited to explore the details and interactions of each object in its surroundings, recognizing the immense value they all have in building greater things.

A few shortcuts are available in live mode:
1 : Toggle the view (fit screen / original size)
T : Toggle paper texture
S : Save current view
H : Re-render in high resolution

The piece might require high processing power depending on its features. A good desktop or laptop running chrome is recommended.

Created with p5.js and GLSL
dmarchi, 2023.

metadata.name: CityScape: Istanbul #48
metadata.description:
Istanbul is a city that straddles the Bosporus Strait, and lies in both Europe and Asia, with a population of over 15 million residents. Most of the population is located in big iconic hills known as the "Seven Hills of Istanbul". 

   In this project, I tried to capture and interpret the daily life routine of the people who live in these hills with the viewing point from Bosphorus. There are three camera angle possibilities to examine the details in different layers. Also, building types, the slope of the hill, and green area density vary in between those scenarios. There are two time zones: day and night. In the night scene, there is a possibility to obtain the crescent moon which is the symbol of the culture inhabits in these lands.

To save as a high-quality image, open in live view and click yes on the incoming prompt.

Created with p5js

metadata.name: Orchard #333
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit. 

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot. Image size is 1000x1000px
Press ‚Äôp‚Äô to pause/resume.

To render a variation at a new size, open live view and append '?size=#' to the end of the URL. The new size may be from 100 to 3,000. This version will not be a 1:1 match to your edition but will have all of the same features.

metadata.name: Paesaggio #138
metadata.description:
In this work I used the tools I learned in developing precedent works to generate a landscape with hills, flowers, streams, ruins, sky and clouds. The generated landscape gives the impression of a natural one but at the same time it has some "abstract" traits that reveal the geometrical properties of the noise generation process. This noise is used both for the morphological aspect and for colors assignment.

Developed with p5.js using WEBGL renderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.

[s] to save a 1600x1600 png.


Features:
"Palette": 12 colormap
"Sky":  Day, Night, Gray - 15% Gray, 20% Night, 65% Day
"Ruins": True, False - 33% True
"Streams": True, False - 33% True
"Flower": Red-Blue, Fuchsia-Yellow, Rose-Violet
"Border": True, False - 25% True


Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Edge #31
metadata.description: This collaboration was destined to happen. The joint effort of two landscape enthusiasts, each with a distinct approach to creation and style, resulted in something new for both. 'Edge' is a project showcasing subtle lines that connect in the subconscious something not opposing but slightly different. It's the edge that separates the dusty country road you're driving on from the beautiful, colorful landscape outside the car window. It's the edge that almost imperceptibly divides day and night during sunrises and sunsets. It's the edge where AI and generative art have converged...

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #977
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan
